    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI’m currently [developing a tree-sitter parser](https://codeberg.org/Freso/tree-sitter-off_taxonomy) for working with files that are inherently multilingual, and it would be _amazing_ to be able to give hints towards what language the spell checker should use. I imagine it could work similar to how `@injection.language` works for code languages.\n\nThis would allow the individual user/client to have spell checking for the language(s) they are familiar with without other languages being dotted will “wrong spelling” markings. E.g., if you have dictionaries installed for Danish and Swedish but not Icelandic or Norwegian, you could get spellchecking on Danish and Swedish without sections specifically in Norwegian (Nynorsk or Bokmål) or Icelandic being checked against Danish or Swedish dictionaries.\n\nOutside of this specific (and admittedly niche) format, this could also be useful for HTML and XML documents with `lang` attributes, `.desktop` files with [localised keys](https://specifications.freedesktop.org/desktop-entry/latest/localized-keys.html), and probably others that are not immediately coming to mind.\n\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nFor a block like\n```off_taxonomy\nen: lemon yogurts\nfr: yaourts au citron\nnl: yoghurts met citroen\ncolor:en: yellow\ndescription:en: a yogurts with lemon inside\ndescription:fr: un yaourt avec du citron\nflavour:en: lemon\n```\nwhere `en`, `fr`, and `nl` gets recognised as `language_code` and the part after `: ` recognised as `text`,\n```scheme\n(line\n  (language_code @spell.language)\n  (text @spell))\n```\nwould instruct Neovim to spellcheck lines 1,4-5,7 against an `en` dictionary, lines 2 and 6 against an `fr` one, and line 3 against a `nl` dictionary.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I don't think there is a real world use case for this in general.\nThe format `<lang>:` is your personal preference and would add additional friction and blur to spell. \n\nWhat you want to archieve is called localization and there are common standards and best practices to implement this externaly... `i18n, l10n, gettext, ...`\n\nFor example in XML: you can do localization either key-based or attribute-based\n```xml\n<!-- key based -->\n<item>\n  <text key=\"hi\">\n    <en>Hello</en>\n    <de>Hallo</de>\n  </text>\n</item>\n\n<!-- attribute based -->\n<item key=\"hi\" lang=\"en\">Hello</item>\n<item key=\"hi\" lang=\"de\">Hallo</item>\n```\n\nSo localization depends explizitly on the schema/spec. There is no general way to do this with `nvim spell`\nAnd exactly this is the problem - People are parsing their XML (etc..) payload without the schema. There is no standard to handle this. The standard is defined in the specific schema.\nThis is more related to a lsp rather than treesitter!?\n\nI don't think it makes sense to implement this small user use-case without an established common standard.\n\n---\nBtw. \nIf Microsoft is so evil, the logical consequence would be to delete your GitHub account.\nI think gh is the wrong place for you to spread your conspiracy theory and propaganda.\n\n<img width=\"1782\" height=\"931\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fe5467a0-162d-4a2b-83f1-23b14849c3f5\" />\n\n\n\n",
